  "local_port": 40924,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Where can I find cheapest property in India?",
  "response": "Finding the cheapest property in India requires research and considering several factors such as location, property type, and market trends. Here are some steps and areas to consider for finding affordable properties in India:\n\n### Steps to Find the Cheapest Property\n\n1. **Research Online Real Estate Platforms:**\n   - Websites like MagicBricks, 99acres, and Housing.com provide listings of properties across India, allowing you to filter by price, location, and type.\n\n2. **Consult Local Real Estate Agents:**\n   - Local agents have in-depth knowledge of the market and can guide you to the most affordable options.\n\n3. **Government Schemes:**\n   - Look into government housing schemes like the Pradhan Mantri Awas Yojana (PMAY), which aims to provide affordable housing.\n\n4. **Consider Tier 2 and Tier 3 Cities:**\n   - Properties in smaller cities are often more affordable compared to metro cities.\n\n### Areas with Cheaper Properties\n\n1. **Uttar Pradesh:**\n   - Cities like Kanpur, Lucknow, and Allahabad offer relatively affordable properties.\n\n2. **Bihar:**\n   - Patna and other smaller towns in Bihar can be budget-friendly options.\n\n3. **Rajasthan:**\n   - Cities like Jaipur, Jodhpur, and Udaipur may have more affordable housing compared to major metros.\n\n4. **Madhya Pradesh:**\n   - Indore and Bhopal offer reasonable property prices.\n\n5. **North-Eastern States:**\n   - States like Assam, Tripura, and Manipur have lower property rates.\n\n6. **Rural and Semi-Urban Areas:**\n   - Properties in rural or semi-urban areas are often significantly cheaper than those in urban centers.\n\n### Additional Tips\n\n- **Negotiate:** Don't hesitate to negotiate the price with sellers or developers.\n- **Consider Resale Properties:** Sometimes, buying a resale property can be cheaper than buying new.\n- **Be Flexible:** Being open to different locations and property types can help you find better deals.\n\nRemember, the cheapest property might not always be the best investment. Always consider factors like future growth potential, infrastructure development, and amenities before making a decision.",
